title: For Sale/Trade:  AMT/IAI Hardballer LONG SLIDE stainless 1911 7" slide
postcontent: #01185 AMT/IAI Hardballer Long Slide for sale. Has the rare and desirable 7 inch barrel and slide. This is the ".45 long slide with laser sighting" from the original Terminator movie. I have addressed all issues these firearms were known for and replaced all problems with Wilson Combat Bulletproof parts. I changed the extractor, fitted bushing, beaver tail grip safety, and skeletonized hammer. The new grip safety gives you a nice, high ride grip, whereas the factory grip safety pushed your hand off of it. I also had the feed ramp reground and polished to cycle any and all ammo-hard ball, hollow points, etc. I also have a new 18# spring in it, that was just test fired and has 2 magazines on it. We also polished the trigger, and it is light and smooth as butter. The pistol is very accurate, very clean, excellent condition- especially being a 30+ year old collector item. I know the original owner who kept it in a safe and rarely shoots. I fixed all the problems and made a nice pistol that will run with the best of em. I am more interested in cash, but may take a really good trade on my end, or a partial trade preferably for something as good as cash. I have plenty of 1911's, and this isn't something I am looking to beat up or compete with, and I don't think beautiful shooters are made to collect dust. I am quite far into this gun with gunsmithing, quality high-end parts, and running it around to different experts to piece together a fantastic shooter. My loss is your gain. Any questions or more pictures are available, just shoot me an email. Great for a collector, shooter, or competitive firearms competition. Thanks for looking!

WWI BAR ammo belt. I'd say it was rebuilt for WWII or maybe even Korea. My uncle carried a BAR all through WWII. He told me the story on this belt. Where the leather pad is, there USED to be a metal cup for the butt of the BAR to be used in "walking fire". In the field, these cups were often removed. They were hard to lay on, and the metal clanged against everything including the gun itself. GI's would remove the cup. My uncle modified his belt this way right after he jumped on D-Day as part of the 17th Airborne. There are 4 mag pouches, the leather pad, and a spot for a pair of .45 mags.
$80 + $15 shipping.

The SA Sports Badge was a decoration of Nazi Germany that was issued between the years 1933 and 1945. It was a political version of the much more generic German Sports Badge which was also issued in great numbers by the Nazis. The SA Sports Badge was issued in three grades (bronze, silver, and gold) as well as a special version known as the "SA Sports Badge for War Wounded". Although originally designed as a physical fitness badge for Nazi stormtroopers, the SA Sports Badge was issued across every German military and paramilitary organization.

title: For Sale:  Modified VEPR 12 (like Saiga 12) Price drop!
postcontent:
Lowered price due to needing money. But price is still firm. Please do not contact me if you are not interested in purchasing for the price listed. I will require state ID and filling out a transfer form just to cover my own butt.

***********REDACTED********

Videos of firearm in action with "Walmart special" Federal 1200 FPS 8 shot: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w2JPS7XkMqI&index=2&list=PLrEG-u9iWTBVCJtC08XY19EEWp3whSt-X

I have for sale a VEPR 12 semi-automatic AK platform shotgun.

 - The barrel has been chopped and a Tromix Monster brake welded on @18.5" (not an SBS). Professionally done by Tac47 here in Houston (a well-known name in the Russian firearm game).

 - Bonesteel side folder installed

 - (2) 5 round Molot magazines included

 - Bolt and trigger group polished by myself

 - CSS low power recoil spring to counter reduced gas pressure of the shorter barrel. Tested and prove. Have videos for proof.

EOTech XPS2 not included


If you're unfamiliar with this firearm, it is a lot like the Saiga 12 but much better:

 - Last round bolt hold open - holds the bolt open on the last round. My favorite feature.

 - "Auto-regulating" gas system - no need to change settings on the gas plug for various loads. Although I'm yet to find any sort of regulator, I think it's just gassed to hell as it has 5 ports in the barrel as opposed to the Saiga's 3.

 - Bolt release button

 - Mag well - No need to "rock and lock" magazines. Just slap them in. This combined with the LRBHO and bolt release makes for nearly AR15-speed reloads.

 - Overall higher quality control, fit and finish.

 - RPK style sights - elevation and windage adjustable

 - The S12 barrel are bored. As in a solid stock with a drill bit ran down the middle. This leads to all kinds of variances. If the bore is a little off center, the barrel wall varies, which creates huge differences in applied gas pressure. The VEPR barrel, like all Molot barrels, is cold hammer forged. Same as the rifles. Better stressing, more consistency with gas pressure and barrel wall. This is the main reason the S12 is not commonly used in competition.

 - hinged and railed dust cover
